-- U.K. Pound Little Changed Versus Dollar Before Mortgage Report
-- B y   L u k a n y o   M n y a n d a
-- 2012-08-30T07:29:43Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-08-30/u-k-pound-little-changed-versus-dollar-before-mortgage-report.html
The pound was little changed against
the dollar before a report economists said will show U.K.
 mortgage approvals  rebounded from an 18-month low.  U.K. 10-year gilts advanced, pushing the yield on the
securities toward a four-week low. Lenders granted 47,000 loans
to buy homes in July, compared with 44,192 the previous month,
the  Bank of England  will say today, according to the median
estimate of 16 analysts in a Bloomberg News survey.  The pound traded at $1.5832 at 8:26 a.m. London time, from
$1.5833 yesterday. It has weakened from $1.5912 on Aug. 23, the
strongest level since May 17. Sterling was at 79.19 pence per
euro, from 79.14 pence yesterday.  Britainâ€™s currency has lost 0.3 percent in the past month,
according to Bloomberg Correlation-Weighted Indexes, which track
10 developed-market currencies. The dollar fell 1.2 percent and
the euro gained 1.3 percent.  The 10-year gilt yield fell two basis points, or 0.02
percentage point, to 1.48 percent. It dropped to 1.46 percent
yesterday, the lowest level since Aug. 3. The 4 percent bond due
in March 2022 rose 0.24, or 2.40 pounds per 1,000-pound face
amount, to 122.31.  U.K. government bonds have returned 3.9 percent this year
through yesterday, according to indexes compiled by Bloomberg
and the European Federation of Financial Analysts Societies.
German bunds gained 3.6 percent and  U.S. Treasuries  earned 2.1
percent.  To contact the reporters on this story:
